<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks on value added tax management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The material submitted informs the progress and results of parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Supervisory Authority, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic's Supervisory Authority, which focused on the field of value added tax management and the use of the VIES information system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) on value added tax).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so the revenue from value added tax affects not only the national budgets of both countries, but also the European Union budget as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions focused mainly on the control of the tax administrators procedure when checking the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system enabled an electronic exchange of information on the registration of value added tax payers in individual Member States of the European Union and on commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The inconsistency between VIES data and the data in the value added tax return submitted by the payer should draw the attention of the tax manager to suspicious cases and allow tax evasion to be detected or. scams.</seg>
<seg id="8">The contribution of parallel checks carried out consisted not only in exchange of information on the financial or financial procedure. the tax authorities in the management of value added tax, but especially in the verification of the use of VIES in checking the application of value added tax exemption in intracommunitary transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained during the implementation of parallel checks is a benefit for the development of cooperation between them and will be used in carrying out further parallel checks in cooperation with the control institutions of Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel Value Added Tax Administration checks for the period from 1. 5. 2004 to 30. 6. 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of inspection: (CZ) Value added tax management, (SK) Control of the tax authority's procedure for the management, control and enforcement of value added tax and performance of tasks within the VIES system to exchange information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Supervisory Authority, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as ′′ NKÚ, the Czech Republic ′′) and the Slovak Republic's Najvyšší SR (hereinafter referred to as ′′ NKÚ SR ′′) concluded a cooperation agreement in the control activity on 12. August 2005</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the parallel control events ′′ Value added tax management ′′ included in the plan of control activity NKÚ, Czech Republic for 2005 under no. 05/19 and ′′ Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the management, control and enforcement of tax on added value and full of tasks within the VIES system on the exchange of information mediated by the Member Landscapes. ", included in the control plan of the NKÚ SR under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel control actions performed were the character of coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated inspection was processed within the meaning of the European Implementing Regulation No. 31 for INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information within the scope of the contract concluded and drawing up a joint final report on the result of parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of a coordinated inspection was to verify selected delivery and acquisition cases in suspicious commercial transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the ′′ SR ′′).</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually committed to each other to provide information from public sources, VIES electronic system (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on accepted and sent requests to verify commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by the department of the state budget and territorial unions of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The Ministry of Finance and 12 financial authorities were controlled by the Ministry of Finance and 12 financial authorities: the IRS in Mladá Boleslav, the Finance Office in Kolín, the Finance Office in Teplice, the Finance Office in Karlovy Vary, the Finance Office in Tábor, the Finance Office in Brno III, the Financial Office in Znojmo, the Financial Office in Znojmo Office in Zlín, Finance office in Šumperku, Ostrava I, Finance office for Prague 7 and the Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspection in the territory of the SR was carried out by the financial and tax section of the NKÚ SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 9 selected tax offices: Bratislava I tax office, Komárno tax office, Trenčín tax office, Prievidza tax office, Tax office Elected, Dolný Kubín tax office, Košice II tax office, Košice V tax office and Michalovka tax office.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of checks:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of parallel control actions was to examine the progress of financial and / or financial. tax authorities in the management of value added tax (VAT) after the inclusion of the Czech Republic and the SR into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the EU) and verify the use of the VIES electronic information system, especially when checking the application of the VAT exemption claim I'm sorry.</seg>
<seg id="27">The controlled period of coordinated inspection was the period from 1. 5. 2004 to 30. 6. 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions In EU Member States, an electronic VIES system is in place, allowing tax administrators to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and in the country of destination it allows the customer to check whether the acquired goods have been properly admitted and taxed.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES system is not centralized within the EU, each Member State is developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The inspection revealed different variations of national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and SR in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">Summary reports indicate the values of delivery of goods to other EU Member States, the values of services provided are not included in the summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from summary reports submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the financial authorities where they compare with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States given in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The financial authorities transmit data from summary reports to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In SR, data from summary reports submitted by Slovak tax payers are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the SR Tax Directorate (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers show the value of supplying goods and the value of providing services to other EU Member States on separate lines of tax returns for VAT, which allows comparing the values given in the summary reports with the value of the supply of goods according to VAT tax returns and identifying their differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the SR, the values of the goods supplied and services provided to other EU Member States are reported summarily on the common line of VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, the SR system does not automatically identify the differences between the value of the supply of goods according to VAT returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the value of supplies of goods in VAT tax returns allows you to use the results of comparison of data when checking the exemption of goods to the EU from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="39">The data delivered from summary reports submitted by payers in other EU Member States are processed into CLO and compared with the value of acquisition of goods given by the payer from the Czech Republic or. SR in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In SR, these data are sent to tax authorities and tax administrators will decide which cases of differences will check.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) will determine which quantified differences between the value of delivery and acquisition of goods must be checked by the tax administrators and transmit a list of such cases to the local authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that the most significant variations will be verified whether VAT has been granted to the right amount of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">The inspection further highlighted some problems in the VAT management system complications caused by different reporting of intracommunitary transactions (i.e. delivery and acquisition of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summary reports are submitted in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum time limit for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">A shortening of the period for which summary reports are submitted to one month, together with a shortening of the deadline for processing them, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">Tax administrators could thus verify more effectively whether VAT was awarded to the correct amount of intracommunitary acquisitions.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, filing tax returns and summary reports for the same tax period (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer reported the same value of the delivery of goods to the EU in the summary report and VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between the values of supply of goods declared by EU payers and the values of acquisition of goods declared by the payers from the Czech Republic or. SR was caused by MJ. different reporting of intracommunitary supply and acquisition data in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">For example, it was the introduction of advances received into summary reports, or the reporting of intracommunitary deliveries in a summary report of the supplier in a different quarter than intracommunitary acquisitions in the tax return to the customer's VAT.</seg>
<seg id="50">Unification of the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would lead to a streamlined monitoring activity of the Member State s' tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of NKU, Czech Republic and NKU SR was also focused on the examination of selected intracommunitary transactions between the two states.</seg>
<seg id="52">A total of 40 cases of commercial transactions between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined together, where there were doubts about their effectiveness or. suspicion of tax evasion on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="53">NKÚ, Czech Republic and NKÚ SR found out, among others. the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities have reported in their VAT tax returns for the purpose of unauthorized tax deduction of excessive VAT transactions, which were not actually implemented;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax operators showed intracommunitary delivery within the carousel shops, which caused a deliberate reduction in the value of deliveries to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers reported in their tax returns for VAT and summary reports intracommunitary supply of VAT exempt goods to buyers who were so-called. ' lost company s' and tax on goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers carried out an intracommunitary supply of goods exempted from VAT for tax entities not registered in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In these cases the VAT supply should not have been exempted and should have been taxed in the country of the supplier;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers reported intracommunitary delivery at higher value in their VAT tax returns than the intracommunitary acquisition, in some cases VAT was incorrect.</seg>
<seg id="60">The knowledge gained in the control action showed that VIES provides tax administrators with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intracommunitary transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax administrators should pay increased attention especially to the thorough examination of the differences between VAT payers and VIES data and the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the Czech Republic and SR accession to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On June 1., 2004, Czech Republic and SR became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">After joining the EU, internal borders and border controls on movement of goods within the EU were abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">The VAT manager was the relevant financial or financial or financial administrator until 30. June 4. tax office, except for goods importation and occasional bus transport in the country where the tax manager was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new law No. 235/2004 Coll., on value added tax (hereinafter referred to as ′′ Law No., 235/2004 Coll."), resp. Act No. 222/2004 Z. z., on value added tax (hereinafter referred to as ′′ Law No., 222/2004 Z. from.") VAT administration has passed on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU Member States from customs offices to financial and responses. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">Delivery of goods in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as the owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">Delivery of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is the supply of goods actually shipped or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">According to the provisions of Section 64 of Law No. 235/2004 Coll. this is an exempted taxable operation with the right to deduct VAT when the goods are delivered to a VAT registered person in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">For the supply of goods, the SR is under the provisions of Section 8 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. considers the supply of material property, where the property rights change.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the country to another Member State shall be considered to be the supply of goods, where such goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on their behalf to another Member State for the purposes of their business.</seg>
<seg id="73">According to the provisions of Section 43 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. is the delivery of goods from the country to another Member State exempted from VAT if the customer is a VAT person in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">The acquisition of goods from another EU Member State is in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 16 of Law No. 235/2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose of goods dispatched or transported by the customer by a VAT registered person in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">Czech payer purchases goods at a price without VAT and its duty is to award VAT in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 25 of Law No. 235/2004 Coll., if the conditions set out in Section 73 of this Act are fulfilled, he is entitled to VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="76">By purchasing goods in the country from another EU Member State, the SR is in accordance with Section 11 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. means the acquisition of the right to dispose of movable material property dispatched or transported by the purchaser by the supplier or by the customer or on their account to the domestic country from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">Tax liability in SR arises when acquiring goods in the country from another Member State under Section 20 of Law No. 222/2004 Z.z.</seg>
<seg id="78">The payer may, according to the provisions of Section 49 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. deduct VAT if the tax is applied by it on the acquisition of goods in the country from another Member State according to the provisions of §§ 11 and 11 a of this law.</seg>
<seg id="79">Trilateral trade is understood according to the provisions of Section 17 of Law No. 235/2004 Coll., resp. Section 45 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. trade between three VAT registered persons in three different EU Member States, where the subject of trade is the supply of the same goods between these three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intracommunitary transactions means the supply and acquisition of goods between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
