<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the value added tax and excise duty management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material provides an overview of the progress and results of parallel control actions carried out by the High Supervisory Authority and the Slovak Republic's Supervisory Authority, which focused on the field of administration given from added value and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the top supervisory authorities of both countries was carried out under a cooperation agreement in control activity concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel control actions has been selected considering the fact that indirect taxes are significantly involved in the revenue of the state budget of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of value added tax, allowing refund of excessive deduction, provides room for tax fraud or tax fraud. Escape.</seg>
<seg id="7">High excise duty rates, especially for tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, make a high profit for those who escape taxation by the illegal sale of these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue in a comprehensive way across the European Union, the VAT Working Group has been created by the highest inspection institutions of the Member States of the European Union, which also includes the highest control offices of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest contribution of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in exchange of experience, but especially in a common effort to identify the problem areas of indirect tax management in order to reduce space for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">Experience gained and knowledge will be used in the planned checks of indirect taxes, mainly focused on the involvement of tax administrators of both states in the VIES system, allowing the movement of goods between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of value added tax and excise duty control for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duty</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the procedure of the tax administrator in the management, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On June 11.2., 2004, a cooperation agreement in the control activity between the Supreme Supervisory Authority (hereinafter referred to as ' NKÚ ') and the Slovak Republic's Supervisory Authority (hereinafter referred to as ' NKÚ SR ') was concluded. The subject of the agreement was cooperation in the parallel control actions carried out ' Value added tax and excise duty ", included in the NKÚ control activity plan for 2004 under no. 04/07 and ′′ Control of the procedure of the administrator dan when managing, checking and enforcement of tax on added value and consumption taxes ", included in the inspection plan NKÚ SR under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted of exchange of information within the scope established by the contract concluded and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties committed in the contract to provide information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from the files of tax entities led by the Czech Republic and tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the Contracting Parties could not obtain when checking the application of the value added tax and excise taxes on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the competent State.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) the inspection was carried out by the state budget and territorial unions of South Bohemia, northeast Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The inspected persons were the Directorate-General of Customs and 12 selected financial authorities: The Finance Office for Prague 1, the Finance Office for Prague 3, the Financial Office in Českých Budějovicích, the Financial Office in Frýdku-Místek, the Finance Office in Hodonin, the Finance Office in Hodonín in Jihlava, the Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Kroměříži, the Financial Office in Písek, the Financial Office in Rožnově pod Radhostem, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Velkém Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspection in the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as ′′ SR ′′) was carried out by the Section of the Tax and Customs Administration of the NKÚ SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 10 tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Bratislava tax office for selected tax entities, Bratislava III tax office, Trnava tax office, Pooh-breeding tax office, Banská Bystrica I tax office, Liptovský Nicholas tax office, Žilina I tax office, Žilina II tax office, Košice I tax office and Tax office Košice IV office.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of inspection</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to examine the fulfilment of financial and / or financial duties. tax offices and customs offices in the management of value added tax and excise duties with a focus on collecting these taxes on import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the SR Customs database and their subsequent verification in tax returns on the relevant financial or financial returns. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="29">The controlled period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recap of inspection results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of the control activity</seg>
<seg id="32">As part of the international cooperation of the NKÚ SR from the Czech Customs database, the NKÚ SR handed over 22 items of uniform customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as ′′ JCD ′′) on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and SR and on the contrary, the NKÚ SR handed over to NKÚ from the Customs database SR 30 221 JCD items.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of the listed JCD items from the Czech Customs database and the SR Customs database was made.</seg>
<seg id="34">Out of 5 selected JCD items from the Czech Customs database, a total of 43 % of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Out of 12 selected JCD items from the SR Customs database, a total of 26 % of JCD related items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on the unassigned JCD items, he was on financial or. the tax offices selected the tax agency files for which imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and SR and financial or. tax authorities have been verified in the territory of the second state that reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and SR were reported.</seg>
<seg id="38">NKÚ and NKÚ SR performed a joint pilot inspection at the border customs crossing of Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, where both interested parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="39">The inspection did not detect deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods made in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation enabled the examination of commercial transactions between trading partners from both States and highlighted the shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="42">In the field of international cooperation, the NKÚ and NKÚ SR control focused on imports and exports of spirits and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">Based on the inspection of tax entities files on selected financial and / or the NKÚ tax authorities asked for verification of exports of goods declared at 40 JCD total statistical value of CZK 15 and NKÚ SR for export verification in statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">NKÚ and NKÚ SR found out the following facts among other things:</seg>
<seg id="45">- commercial transactions were not declared on both sides in the same way, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the Czech Republic customs database and the customs database of the SR,</seg>
<seg id="46">- error in entering data into customs databases prevented certain imports from identifying or identifying. exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- some exports from the Czech Republic have not been demonstrated by adequate imports into SR.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is reason to suspect fictional exports of goods for the purpose of unauthorized application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax agencies did not comply with certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- in the activities of financial or financials tax offices were identified in the management of value added tax and excise duty and in their synergy with customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the field of value added tax and excise duty, attention will continue to be needed to be paid to international trade in order to minimize tax evasion effectively.</seg>
<seg id="52">The improvement of tax administrators's activity in the performance of value added tax administration is important.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis of effective control of excise duties is the control of documents circulation, systematic physical inspection of goods and exchange of information with each other when goods are imported and exported.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of value added tax and excise duty status</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as 'VAT') was collected by financial and / or financial. tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out in the country and customs offices on importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenue was for financial or financial income the tax authorities are given the difference between chosen own tax liability and excessive VAT deductions refunded.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenue at customs offices was given the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax collected by the customs authorities, in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, reflected in the tax deductions applied to financial and / or financial tax. tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">Most financial or financial ones tax authorities exceeded excessive VAT deductions above the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget revenue, since it participated in the tax revenue of the Czech Republic's budget in 2003 and about 42 % in the tax revenue of the state budget of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">Total VAT collection in the Czech Republic reached 162,9 billion in 2003..</seg>
<seg id="63">In 2003, the financial and customs authorities collected a total of 394,3 billion for VAT. Kč and excessive VAT refunds were totaled 231,4 billion...</seg>
<seg id="64">Total VAT recovery in SR amounted to 83,8 billion in 2003 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003 tax and customs authorities collected 187,0 billion for VAT. Sk and excessive VAT refunds amounted to a total of 103,2 billion. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as ′′ SpD ′′) was carried out by the relevant financial and / or financial respectively tax authorities and imports of products subject to SpD by customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of SpD in the tax revenue of the state budget in the Czech Republic was around 16 % in 2003 and in SR about 19 %.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total SpD collection selected in the Czech Republic by the financial and customs offices in 2003 was 85,6 billion. Kč and in SR it reached 38,0 billion. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. The course of the inspection action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between NKÚ and NKÚ SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from customs databases of the Czech Republic and SR, in the second stage the results of this comparison were used in mutual verification of the realization of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the SR and during checks carried out in the territory of both states.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel VAT and SpD checks was presented at a working meeting of representatives of NKÚ and NKÚ SR in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003 there was a coordination meeting, including him. selection of commodities agreed - types of goods that posed a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax rules: - alcohol and spirit drinks, customs tariff items No 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, customs tariff items No. 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff items and subheadings No. 8471 and 30 8473, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff subheadings No. 8525 91 20, 8525 99 20, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">The two parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be carried out: (a) from unassigned items found by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the SR, (b) from entities making imports and exports regularly or on a single basis in large volume, (c) based on findings from checks carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and SR</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities tested for the month of October 2002 tested the mechanism for the mutual allocation of JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
