<seg id="1">Procurement of public works contracts and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel control carried out by the Czech Supreme Supervisory Authority (NKÚ) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Procurement of public procurement for goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and private sphere.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources in the most efficient and economical way possible and ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU) public procurement is a key factor for the success of the single economic space.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set limits in its regulations, where the contracting authority must meet certain requirements to guarantee a wide and unlimited competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States therefore need to transpose the European procurement right into their national rules and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public procurement that is value below EU limits, regulation of their award remains within the scope of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption with subsequent high potential of damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and incorrect advantage (corruption prevention).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Supervisory Authority of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel checks in the field of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as it was transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The checks included procurement below European limits to affect corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control findings of the two top control institutions are summarized in a joint report, which is addressed, among other things, to international organisations such as the International Organization of Highest Supervisory Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Control areas and controlled institutions</seg>
