<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">The European Parliament and the Council of the European Union have adopted, inter alia, a directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, supply and services in order to ensure the free movement of goods and services and a directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to review procedures on the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (review directive), with these two directives being transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU general procurement principles include in particular: a requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or a discrimination; a requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include the directive on the coordination of procedures for public procurement includes provisions on construction projects whose total expected value is or exceeds 5 miles. €.</seg>
<seg id="120">These clauses affect: Content documentation content; type of procurement used; publication of certain information before, during and after the end of the procedure; compliance with the deadline for acceptance of tenders; qualifying requirements that may be required of tenderers; criteria for the selection of the most suitable offer.</seg>
