<seg id="756">The obligation to document the procurement procedure is in accordance with the essential requirement of the principle of transparency applied at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision making and justification guarantees transparency in the procurement process, and above all guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each candidate in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, since the obligation to substantiate individual decisions and their justification significantly reduces the space for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In cases of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must announce their completion of the EU's Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and thus fulfils the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarize the essential information on its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics, which allow for an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have completely transposed into their national legislation the provisions of the European documentation and notification laws.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notifications for European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different clauses</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to announce the award of a contract does not only apply to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The deadline for notification is only 15 days after the contract is concluded.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those compulsory under European law, applies only to limited procedures exceeding the limit of 25 thousand. € (625 thousand. Kč) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of 15 thousand. € (375 thousand. Kč) VAT incl.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only parties are informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main inspection findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">Large amount of assignments have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. reasons for supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it contracted a candidate whose offer did not contain compulsory elements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Disclosure of award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of some European procedures, the contracting authority made mistakes in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In case of several assignments, evidence of publication of the notice was missing.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">Statistically proven files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, contract information was not published due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The contracting authority took six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not published during this period.</seg>
<seg id="789">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">The events related to the organizing of a major sporting event have been identified considerable shortcomings in the procurement documentation such as: incorrect information on offer prices in protocols from the evaluation committee meeting.</seg>
<seg id="792">Moreover, some documents about opening envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Disclosure of award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="794">In preparation of repairs and maintenance of communications, highway construction and road circuit, public procurement notice was sent after the deadline or not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">Documentation and notification and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech reporting duties are somewhat stricter compared to German.</seg>
<seg id="799">The checks revealed shortcomings significantly lowering the value of documentation as a means of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="800">This segmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel checks of NKÚ and BRH were focused on two areas that are essential for the process of procurement both in the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU Legislative gives opportunity to international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">The aim of measures to prevent corruption is not only to avoid it or at least reduce it, but also to prevent financial damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The sought inspection findings of both control institutions - NKÚ and BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement right of both countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions give an internal view of common and different elements that can help both countries in the further development and application of this right.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries transposed EU law regarding public procurement into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">Thus, there is an important common basis in both countries for public procurement and fulfilling essential requirements in the area of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting entities reinforce these requirements with partially very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has raised public procurement clauses requiring European management and procedures that are below EU limits and therefore governs national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, checks showed that contracting entities do not always fully comply with all relevant EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures to eliminate the mentioned irregularities taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, checks identified risks affecting economy and achieving value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">In particular, this is an incomplete definition of the subject-matter of a public contract resulting in additional works, which were often awarded against the law, insufficient definition of the expected price and also the required qualifying assumptions narrowing the possible circuit of tenderers and thus reducing competition especially in the field of transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">Joint checks were not intended to detect corruption cases.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and NKÚ do not have the tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can verify whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulate during public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">In terms of corruption prevention, both countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">The German provisions mainly give space to wide and unlimited competition, transparency and controls as a central element of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="822">Czech regulations mainly monitor the strengthening of the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany there are general principles of corruption prevention that apply to the whole Federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles were also incorporated among the public procurement requirements and were adopted to meet the specific needs of these procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes very precisely, ways to comply with the requirements for the prevention of corruption during the procurement procedure and the choice of persons included therein.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the opinion of the BRH, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate instrument for substantial reduction of the risk of corruption in public procurement, while limiting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate control (especially the principle of cross control), requirements regarding transparency, procurement documentation and various organisational measures are also an effective mechanism to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">Therefore, BRH does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions must comply with during the award of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting entities should provide their employees with further education and thus inform them with anti-corruption requirements and further increase their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the exposed weaknesses applies to activities delegated by the construction administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls in delegation of powers increases the risk of their abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Consequently, manipulation and corruption activities should only be transmitted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorized intervention.</seg>
<seg id="836">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic anti-corruption strategies were adopted at the government level, which also significantly affect the public procurement area.</seg>
<seg id="838">NKÚ control events took place during the implementation of one of the most important parts of this strategy, a significant change in the public procurement law and the adoption of follow-up implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">Strategy adopted and new laws can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">According to new regulations, for example, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the contract, the determination of the expected value of the contract, the adequacy of requirements for qualifying assumptions, the determination of basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of tenders and the proper improvement and publication of everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendation</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both NKÚ and BRH have a positive opinion on the ways of implementing EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their wide application in practice confirmed that EU requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">A multinational model established in the EU can also serve as a base for similar projects aimed at facilitating and supporting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential of material and intangible damage caused as a result of manipulation and corruption in connection with the award of public procurement, both BRH and NKÚ insist that it is the responsibility of contracting entities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and improve them wherever possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">Especially organisational structures and procurement processes should be monitored continuously in terms of weaknesses and risks to identify and respond appropriately to the need for repair actions.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it appeared that the share of open procurement procedures should increase in the Czech Republic, which give space to competition and significantly reduce the possibility of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">Procurement in parts can also have a positive impact on the price achieved in cases where it is admissible and suitable for contracting entities. The higher number of applicants puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The influence on the procurement procedure is also provided by his organization.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organizations, while in the Czech Republic, except for transport buildings, central authorities organize it themselves or through contractors.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both NKÚ and BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work where it is in place and address them with their parliament and government beyond their common project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they believe that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Highest Supervisory Institutions (INTOSAI), because these principles and findings are of general importance for effective countering corruption and guarantee, that public procurement is awarded in a regime of well functioning and honest competition and that value is achieved for money.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
