<p>
<seg id="1">COMMON FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel checks on the management of excise taxes in SR and Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">The highest supervisory office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Supervisory Authority of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The Joint Report submitted informs about the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel checks carried out by the Slovak Republic's Supreme Supervisory Authority and the Czech Republic's Supervisory Authority, with a focus on the management of excise taxes in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the top control institutions of both countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the NKÚ SR and the NKÚ Czech Republic in the performance of parallel inspections focused on the management of excise taxes, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel checks was selected based on the fact that both EU Member States are based on common European legislation to find out how it is applied at national level, how the excise tax management system is set up and how the systems in SR and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out was exchanging experience, identifying differences and finding good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, it was beneficial to find that international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise duty management is very limited without parallel checks being carried out.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrík,</seg>
<seg id="14">President of the President</seg>
<seg id="15">Chairman</seg>
<seg id="16">The highest supervisory office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">The highest inspection office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel checks of SPD management in SR and Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation of excise duties in the Czech Republic and the SR and their administration is in accordance with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences were found between the adjustment of excise duties in SR and Czech Republic, in the Czech Republic contributes to the effective management of excise duties verification of the economic stability of applicants for the issuance of permits and compulsory marking and coloring of selected mineral oils and some other oils; in SR the distribution of control signs is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdened by the tax manager.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise tax evasion, the supervision of raw tobacco movement and or as a good practice in both countries. tobacco raw materials, implementation of the Institute of Fuel Distributor and registration of retailers of alcohol packaging.</seg>
<seg id="23">Excise tax revenue in SR and Czech Republic grows slower than other tax revenue.</seg>
<seg id="24">EU goals consisting of reducing labour taxation, introducing ecologically economical measures and reducing tobacco and alcohol addiction have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and SR, among others. also because there is no indexation of excise duty rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This results in reducing the importance of excise taxes on total tax revenue and due to increasing purchasing power, a real reduction in tax burden with excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="26">The state has long-term support for the implementation of environmental measures, but these measures have a negative impact on excise tax revenue, which will need to be replaced by other revenue or reducing state spending.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative costs incurred on the management of excise taxes in the Czech Republic and the SR have been growing long-term, mainly due to wage growth, and their efficiency is decreasing.</seg>
<seg id="28">In SR, this effectiveness is negatively affected by the costs of electronization of excise duty management (IT expenditure) and the costs incurred on the wages of employees carrying out permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses on alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">Electronization of the management of excise taxes in SR did not significantly improve the number of tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="30">NKÚ Czech Republic and NKÚ SR recommend doporučují SR to rethink the justification of the performance of permanent tax oversight in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the effectiveness of administrative expenses was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the controlled period, which would lead to a reduction in the staffing of the excise duty management.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative actions of tax administrators was similar in SR and the Czech Republic in the various years of the controlled period, but the number of comparable tax entities is about a third lower in SR than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in SR perform administrative actions mainly in the form of physical exercise of tax oversight, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote oversight and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">The management of excise taxes in SR is more administratively demanding than in the Czech Republic and due to the ratio of the number of tax operations to the number of entities and more costly.</seg>
<seg id="35">Electronization of excise duty management in SR and Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">In SR, the administration of tax returns for excise duties is fully electronized, documents demonstrating taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are transmitted in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both methods of electronization support effective management of excise taxes and therefore NKÚ Czech Republic and NKÚ SR recommend applying them not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditure on the implementation of the EMCS system could not be compared as the FG SR provided spending data only for the system upgrade in the period 2011-2015, but the costs were incurred even before this period.</seg>
<seg id="39">Expenditure incurred during this period only for the EMCS upgrade was about 20 % higher in the SR than the costs incurred in the Czech Republic both on the introduction of EMCS and on the upgrade of this system in over ten years.</seg>
<seg id="40">Excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and SR did not achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when comparable spending was incurred.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of supervisory is comparable in both countries, but in the SR, the management of excise taxes is significantly more resource demanding.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of an electronic system for monitoring the movement of excise products (EMCS) has been streamlined by the management of excise duties, but in SR to a lower extent, because significantly higher costs were incurred than in the Czech Republic on the introduction of the system and its modernization.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">The cooperation of both supervisory institutions was carried out under the Cooperation Treaty on the implementation of parallel checks aimed at the management of excise duties on 18. 8. 2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">NKÚ Czech Republic and NKÚ SR agreed to perform parallel checks, which will primarily focus on the issue of excise duty management and whose results will allow analysis, comparisons and evaluation of the facts found.</seg>
<seg id="46">Common audit issues were agreed on which parallel checks were based.</seg>
<seg id="47">Characteristics of the object and the aim of parallel control:</seg>
<seg id="48">The aim of parallel checks was to compare the performance of excise tax administrators, taking into account qualitative and quantitative indicators and identifying weaknesses of the excise tax management process.</seg>
<seg id="49">The following main audit questions should have been answered in particular:</seg>
<seg id="50">Did excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and SR achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when incurring comparable expenditures?</seg>
<seg id="51">Has the introduction of an electronic system for monitoring the movement of excise duty products (Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS) been streamlined and the costs incurred effectively for its introduction?</seg>
<seg id="52">Parallel checks carried out should have identified causes of significant differences affecting the efficiency and effectiveness of tax management in the Czech Republic and SR, especially in the field of regulation and organisational structure.</seg>
<seg id="53">This segmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="54">The Directorate-General of Customs (DGC) and the Finance Directorate of SR (FG SR) joined the Joint Declaration on the cooperation of the Visegrad Four countries, among the aims of this Declaration include the field of excise duties, the fight against fraud, exploring the possibility of harmonizing legislation and seeking harmonised interpretations on rules of selected problems, exploring the possibility of common activities to increase efficiency in fraud detection and sharing experience and best practice.</seg>
<seg id="55">1 EMCS is operated under Decision No 1 of the European Parliament and of the Council. Article 1152/2003 (1152/2003) EC of 16. June 2003 on the introduction of an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of excise products.</seg>
<seg id="56">Identification of the inspection performed by the NKÚ Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="57">Control number: 15/33</seg>
<seg id="58">Subject of control: Excise tax management</seg>
<seg id="59">Objective of inspection: The aim of the NKÚ Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of customs authorities in the management of excise duties, especially when monitoring transport in the suspension system and ensuring tax (customs debt); to check whether the excise duty management system is set up to be Efficiency of the revenue collection of the state budget ensures.</seg>
