<seg id="68">Legislative for excise duties in Czech Republic and SR</seg>
<seg id="69">Excise tax management legislation is divided into EU legislation (see Annex No. 1) and national law level (see Annex No. 2).</seg>
<seg id="70">Council Directive 2008/118 / EC on the general adjustment of excise duties and repealing Directive 92/12 / EEC defines excise duty and lays down the basic rules for the management of taxes and the management of energy products and electricity, tobacco products, alcohol and alcoholic beverages.</seg>
<seg id="71">This directive provides for the imposition of taxes on consumption on other products.</seg>
<seg id="72">EU legislation regulates in particular the minimum conditions for: the amount of tax rates for the different types of selected products, production, storage, processing and possession of taxable products, taxation, exemption and tax refund, oversight of transport of selected products between EU Member States, international cooperation and keeping registers on economic operators and tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="73">EU legislation enables control procedures and institutes to be introduced at national level, provided that they do not distort competition.</seg>
<seg id="74">Legislative of excise duties in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="75">Definition of legislation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="76">In the Czech Republic, the legislation of excise duties is concentrated in the excise duty law (law no. 353/2003 Coll.), which regulates the management of mineral oil tax, alcohol tax, tobacco tax, beer taxes, wine and intermediate taxes and raw tobacco tax.</seg>
<seg id="77">This law defines forms of handling products subject to excise duties, tax payer, permitting proceedings, conditions for transport of products, tax return and penalties for infringements.</seg>
<seg id="78">The law and follow-up decrees further modify some other conditions for handling mineral oils (marking of mineral oils), restrictions on the sale of spirit drinks and tobacco products, monitoring the handling of special mineral oils and storage of crude tobacco for a purpose other than the production of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="79">Taxes on other energy products (i.e. natural gas and some other gases, solid fuels and electricity) are regulated in sections 45 to 47 of Law No. 261/2007 Coll., on stabilization of public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="80">In the Czech Republic there are also a number of provisions related to the management of excise duties contained in special legislation. Fuel Act No. 311/2006 Coll. and the implementing regulation regulates the conditions for the sale, distribution of fuel and keeping fuel records for free tax circulation.</seg>
<seg id="81">In law no. 61/1997 Coll., o alcohol and its implementing rules define the conditions for manufacture, storage, registration and control of the production and circulation of alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="82">Act No. 307/2013 Coll., on compulsory alcohol marking and relevant implementing regulations provide for compulsory marking of alcohol in the packaging, conditions for handling control bands and conditions for alcohol handling (i.e. for the manufacture, processing, sale or other transfer, transport, transport, storage, takeover, use, possession, import or export of alcohol).</seg>
<seg id="83">Tax procedures not specified in special regulations are governed by law No. 280/2009 Coll., tax order.</seg>
<seg id="84">The penalties are imposed in accordance with law no. 500/2004 Coll., administrative order.</seg>
<seg id="85">Conditions for the issue of a trade licence (concession) for the operation of a business ′′ production and processing of fuels and greases and distribution of fuel ′′ and ′′ production, modification and sale of fermented alcohol, alcohol of consumerism and spirit drinks ′′ are governed by law No. 455/1991 Coll., on business (business law).</seg>
<seg id="86">The Czech Republic has exercised the right to introduce control procedures and institutes to control the transport of selected products in free tax circulation and to supervise compliance with the legislation in the handling of selected products without excise duty, as well as the handling of selected products already taxed taken away.</seg>
<seg id="87">This is a monitoring of the handling of special mineral oils and crude tobacco, marking some other mineral oils, marking tobacco products and alcohol in consumer packaging.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Czech Republic used the authorization to apply excise duty to other products and introduced an excise duty on raw tobacco as one of the measures against tax fraud.</seg>
<seg id="89">Structure of changes in legislation for individual types of excise duties in relation to the subject matter of inspection in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="90">Based on the resolution of the Government of the Czech Republic of 3. October 2012 No. 735, the implementation of the ′′ zero tolerance plan for the black market for spirit drinks ", between 2012-2015 and 2012-2015 in the Czech Republic, fundamental legislative arrangements were introduced in the Czech Republic, which introduced a number of measures against tax fraud on alcohol excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="91">During the same period there were also major changes in the legislation on mineral oil tax, tobacco product taxes and the criminality of preparation of tax reduction.</seg>
<seg id="92">Criminal protection of tax revenue</seg>
<seg id="93">Effective from 1. 7. 2016, the crime preparation of the crime is introduced ′′ tax reduction, fee and similar compulsory payment ". The adjustment made should allow police authorities to take more efficient and timely measures to reduce tax fraud, e.g. deployment of operational resources.</seg>
<seg id="94">General provisions for the management of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="95">The issuance of an authorization to handle excise products under the Excise Tax Act is conditional on: reliability; debtlessness; economic stability; right to operate a business allowing the pursuit of an activity related to the authorization; a situation where the appellant not in liquidation or bankruptcy.</seg>
<seg id="96">The aim of the regulation was mainly to address the issue of tax arrears, by reducing operators with the right to handle excise taxable products.</seg>
<seg id="97">The condition of economic stability newly enables the tax manager to take into account the financial situation of tax entities both in the framework of the authorization procedure and after the issuance of the authorization.</seg>
<seg id="98">The purpose of this measure is to prevent entities not having sufficient financial income to properly fulfil tax liabilities from handling selected products.</seg>
<seg id="99">Indicators (profitability, liquidity, financial stability, activity, productivity, labor productivity) were established to assess the economic stability of the appellant.</seg>
<seg id="100">In addition to these indicators, the administrative discretion of the tax manager is also important in view of the individual conditions of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="101">The law sets out the periodicity of verification of the fulfilment of the condition of economic stability because of the current data - verification takes place once a year following the deadline for filing income tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tax administrator has the opportunity to lay down other conditions needed for tax management.</seg>
<seg id="103">If the holder of the permit does not fulfil the conditions, the tax manager is entitled to revoke the permit or cancel with delay.</seg>
<seg id="104">Out of the total of 2 609 entities with the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic examined the condition of economic stability, 18,6 % were found economically unstable with high risk of arrears when the tax liability exceeds the amount of tax security (e.g. repeated recipient).</seg>
