<seg id="935">The EMCS system ensures the receiving and dispatch of excise goods by tax entities entitled to use the EMCS system, thus reducing the risk of tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="936">The biggest development of functionalities occurred in 2011, when EMCS was fully introduced into operation (see Annex No. 6).</seg>
<seg id="937">Expenditure on the introduction and use of EMCS system</seg>
<seg id="938">The introduction of EMCS was implemented as another module of application equipment SysNeD and therefore it is not possible to accurately determine the amount of costs of its initial application on the Slovak side.</seg>
<seg id="939">Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="940">Comparison</seg>
<seg id="941">The aim of EMCS was to replace a system based on administration of transport in a documentary form.</seg>
<seg id="942">The benefit of EMCS system is a comprehensive overview of transport between Member States within the EU from the notification of transport to its termination - reducing administrative costs for tax administrators and tax operators for processing, transfer and document archiving is important.</seg>
<seg id="943">In the Czech Republic and SR, national functionality has been introduced into EMCS system, allowing traffic monitoring in a conditional system between two places in the Czech Republic or. in SR.</seg>
<seg id="944">In addition, automatic functionality of online monitoring and ensuring a guarantee for excise duty is applied in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="945">A national functionality is also introduced to monitor the risk of the tax entity or. Transportation, with subsequent compulsory response by the tax manager.</seg>
<seg id="946">The SR and the Czech Republic register a comparable number of transport within the EU in the EMCS system.</seg>
<seg id="947">However, the costs incurred in SR to upgrade this system were byly 744 higher between 2012 and 2015 than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="948">NKÚ SR received data from the FR SR on upgrade of EMCS system only for the period from 2011, although this system has been established and operated before.</seg>
<seg id="949">Yet the costs incurred on upgrading EMCS system in SR were byly 188 higher than the costs of introducing and upgrading the EMCS system in about ten years of its operation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="950">Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="951">For a controlled period, the volume of expenditure related to the EMCS upgrade in SR in conversion to one transport exceeds costs of the same type in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="952">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="953">The cooperation of the Czech Republic and the NKU SR met the goals.</seg>
<seg id="954">Both control institutions gained a deeper knowledge of the excise tax management system in the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="955">Despite the common basic legal framework, it has been found that there are significant differences in both tax systems that affect the efficiency of the management of excise taxes.</seg>
<seg id="956">During parallel checks, examples of good practice were found, which could contribute to reducing tax fraud, their importance with rising tax rates will increase.</seg>
<seg id="957">Procedures have also been identified to reduce the cost of excise duty management.</seg>
<seg id="958">Cross-cooperation has revealed differences that significantly affect tax management efficiency and limit international comparison unless mutually coordinated deep checks are carried out with tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="959">In this the role of the highest control institutions is irreplaceable.</seg>
