<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel control of value added tax management carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lim Declaration of 1977 emphasizes that the Supreme Supervisory Institutions (SAI) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenue to be controlled to the extent possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The European Organization of the Highest Supervisory Institutions (EUROSAI) considers it one of the most important components of public tax revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">VI. EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 dealt with the audit of SAI public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="7">An important step towards optimizing SAI control activity is the development of a special strategy for public revenue auditing.</seg>
<seg id="8">This applies especially to taxes as the most complex source of public income, which is most prone to great losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">Since the economies of individual states are increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may, to some extent, be unable to carry out a control activity without cooperating with the SAI of another state.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is an audit of internationally organized fraud, which causes significant losses in the revenue of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In order to combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">SAIs that carry out the inspection in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation between themselves.</seg>
<seg id="13">Just on VI. the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn was created by the idea of checking the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as ′′ VAT ′′) and VIES system in the cooperation of the Supreme Supervisory Authority and the Federal Court of Auditors, Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">Careful preparation followed, when both parties first had to acquaint themselves with the legal environment and procedures for VAT management in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of control topics included in the control programme was made.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving effective and efficient VAT management is a long-term problem and individual states (especially Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve, simplify and make the collection of this tax available.</seg>
<seg id="17">We believe that the results of our control can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrators, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the international information exchange system.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel checks on value added tax management performed in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Control number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2-2005-1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Value added tax administration after the Czech accession to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Verification of administrative cooperation in value added tax under Council Regulation (EC) No Commission Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the control action in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the management of value added tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter the EU) associated with the free movement of goods and services and to check the use of the VIES system, especially when checking the application of the value added tax exemption for intracommunitary delivery.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the inspection was to examine the system of control of intracommunitary value added tax with a special focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the abovementioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">The system of exchange of value added tax information The Surveillance Authority, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as ′′ NKÚ ′′) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter ′′ BRH ′′) in mutual cooperation under a contract concluded between the two inspection institutions on 8. June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the verification of selected commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as ′′ Germany ′′), the use of information obtained by means of international cooperation between tax administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">Joint final report on the results of the inspection actions has been processed within the meaning of the European Directive No. 31 to implement INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The period controlled was from 1. August 2004 to 31. August 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">Parallel VAT management inspection in Czech Republic and Germany was performed under agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">Outside the main point - exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No Commission Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 1925/2004-the inspection covered other topics, such as payer registration, VAT tax returns and summary reports closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, part of the inspection included the legal situation in the international bus transport of passengers and comparing some statistics.</seg>
<seg id="36">The comparison of the VAT management systems of both countries identified differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany business owners are registered regardless of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, the first criterion (among others) is for registration exceeding the limit laid down in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, only one tax identification number is assigned to payers, which they also use in intracommunitary transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, VAT payers are assigned a tax number, used only for business transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German payer intends to carry out intracommunitary transactions, he must request an assignment of a special identification number called. VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">Since different methods of registration cause problems, conditions should be offset throughout the EU (see. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus transport of persons.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus transport of persons is exempted from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, part of the shipment taking place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">At EU level efforts should be made to harmonise the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of VAT (see. 4.2)</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT tax return.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic, payers filed tax returns only for individual tax periods (month or quarter), in Germany, payers are entitled to submit so-called. preliminary tax returns for VAT (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year they must submit an annual VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike the Czech Republic of payers, payers in Germany are obliged to submit preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of the obligation to submit VAT tax returns in the Czech Republic electronically would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While the payers report summary reports to the financial authorities in the Czech Republic, the payers report summary reports to the CLO in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="53">Therefore, data from summary reports are available immediately after submission of the financial authorities in Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="54">German financial authorities have information from summary reports only after processing it into CLO.</seg>
<seg id="55">Fighting VAT fraud requires updated intra-communitarian transaction information to be available as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="56">Monthly summary reporting would shorten the time shift between the date of transaction and VIES data update.</seg>
<seg id="57">This would subsequently allow early examination of taxation in the Member State of the customer (see. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="58">Which would, however, require all Member States to accept the same deadline for submitting a summary report.</seg>
<seg id="59">5) International exchange of VAT information.</seg>
<seg id="60">Czech CLO monitors the three-month deadline for information received.</seg>
<seg id="61">German CLO does not follow the past time.</seg>
<seg id="62">Consequently, the German tax administration dealt with significantly lower percentage of the applications received within the specified deadline.</seg>
<seg id="63">Due to these problems, BRH recommended the German CLO to carry out permanent warnings (see. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="64">6) Risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="65">Each of the two Member States develop their own risk management system (hereinafter referred to as ′′ RMS ′′) that has its strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="66">NKÚ and BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="67">Successful criteria, components and approaches of RMS must be exchanged and introduced in each EU Member State, otherwise the scammers will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the cooperation, both SAIs tested selected cases of intracommunitary transactions between tax entities from the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="69">Thirty-one cases of commercial transactions were examined together with the application of the CLO legislation, where there were doubts about their effectiveness or suspicion of tax evasion on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="70">It was found that:</seg>
<seg id="71">In some cases, the tax authorities used information obtained through international cooperation and measured VAT tax liability for the payers.</seg>
<seg id="72">In these cases, payers either unduly claimed the right to exemption from VAT or did not admit the acquisition of goods in VAT tax return.</seg>
<seg id="73">In some cases the financial authorities could not use the information obtained because the information was either incomplete or incomprehensible.</seg>
<seg id="74">In other cases the information could not be used due to various legal provisions in both Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to respond to the request for information.</seg>
<seg id="76">Cases were found where payers misplaced commercial transactions in summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="77">As a result, VIES data were incorrect and tax administration had to check these cases (see. 6.).</seg>
