<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in checks on excise duty management between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The joint report submitted informs about the progress and outcome of international cooperation during parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Supervisory Authority, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic's High Supervisory Authority, focused on the management of excise duties during the period after the entry of both countries into the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation was implemented under a control activity cooperation agreement concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel checks has been selected with a view to the fundamental change in the system of excise duty collection, which has occurred in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union since 1. May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of non-taxable goods until the date of delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, new legislation, adopted in both countries, allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under tax exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great claims on tax administrators and envisages a mutual close synergies of the competent administrative authorities of the Member States in combating tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in checks on excise duty management from 1. May 2004 to 31. December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (Czech Republic) Excise Tax Administration (SR) Procedure of colonial authorities in the management of consumption taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Supervisory Authority, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the ′′ NKÚ-Czech Republic ′′) and the Slovak Republic's Supervisory Authority (hereinafter referred to as ′′ NKÚ SR ′′) concluded on 8. February 2006 a cooperation agreement in control activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel checks ′′ Excise Tax Administration ", included in the plan of the NKÚ-Czech Republic control activity for 2005 under no. 05/34, and ′′ Control of the procedure of colnesian authorities in the management of consumption taxes ", included in the NKÚ SR control plan for 2006 under no. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel checks were the character of coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information that the Contracting Parties could not obtain during the inspection of the management of excise duties in the territory of their state and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks in the sense of the European implementing directives for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards - Directive No. 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the territory of the Czech Republic, groups inspected from the state budget department and from the territorial unions of Central Bohemia, South Bohemia, West Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, Northeast Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia between 7. February to June 2., 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The controlled persons were the Directorate-General of Customs (hereinafter referred to as ′′ DGC ′′) and 11 financial authorities.</seg>
<seg id="21">12 selected customs offices were checked within the DGC out of 54. total.</seg>
<seg id="22">The section of the financial and tax NKÚ SR in cooperation with exposures NKÚ SR Banská Bystrica and Košice on 5 customs offices out of 9 between 13. February and 2. from 2. February to 2. 2006. June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">8 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of parallel checks was to examine the procedure of customs authorities in the management of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation focused on the procedure of tax administrators in the exercise of supervision of transport of excise goods, especially on the registration of initiated and terminated transport under the conditioned tax exemption regime, and on the exchange of information under mutual administrative assistance between the managers of excise duties of the Czech Republic and the SR.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Excise duty management</seg>
<seg id="27">The management of excise duties in the Czech Republic was carried out by financial authorities until 31. December 2003</seg>
<seg id="28">Since 1. January 2004, the customs authorities, which have only levied excise duty on imports, took over this agenda.</seg>
<seg id="29">Excise tax is subject to mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products in Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="30">The revenue of the state budget from excise taxes in the Czech Republic was totaled 82,8 billion in 2004 Kč and on the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees of 424,7 billion. Kč excise duties participated in 19,5 %.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the revenue of the state budget from excise duties amounted to 103,6 billion. Kč and share of the state budget revenue from taxes and fees of 460.4 460.4 billion. Kč was 22,5 %.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from the excise duty on mineral oils to the state budget was 80 % of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 was 90,9 %.</seg>
<seg id="33">Difference to 100 % of 13 billion. Kč in 2004 and 6,9 billion. Kč in 2005 was the income of the State Transport Fund.</seg>
<seg id="34">Customs authorities have been executed by all excise duties in SR since 1. May 2004, except for excise duty on mineral oil, which they have been administered since 1 1. edna 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, tax authorities were exercising the management of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="36">Excise duty in SR is subject to mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="37">The revenue of the state budget from excise taxes in SR was 43.4 billion in 2004 Sk and on total tax revenue of 209,5 billion. Sk excise duties participated in 20,7 %.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005 the revenue of the state budget from excise duties was 50 billion. Sk and on total tax revenue of 222,6 billion. Sk excise duties participated in 22,5 %.</seg>
