<p>
<seg id="1">Value added tax management in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are generally a key source of public income.</seg>
<seg id="5">It is therefore obvious that the Supreme Audit Institutions (SAI) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example is value added tax fraud (hereinafter also ′′ VAT ′′).</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, EUR 100 billion is estimated in the European Union (hereinafter the ′′ EU ′′) each year.</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005 participants VI. the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">Within this cooperation, SAI can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very appropriate area for control cooperation, since it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Czech Republic's Supreme Supervisory Authority (hereinafter referred to as ′′ NKÚ ′′) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, also ′′ BRH ′′) performed the first parallel VAT control action in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since VAT fraud is not limited to a single country, but is expanded across the EU, close cooperation between SAI is required to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to address this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Therefore both SAIs decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a parallel check.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2-2009-0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Control subject: (CZ) Value added tax management (D) Bilateral audit with NKÚ (follow-up check)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the control action was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the management of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for solving selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as ′′ Germany ′′), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the context of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The inspection action was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement recommendations issued by NKÚ and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other VAT related areas.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting inspection findings were intended to compare with the established best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The period controlled was the years 2006 to 2008, in case of factual context and the period preceding and following, until the end of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The subsequent VAT management check in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">Suspicious cases of intracommunitary transactions were detected during previous parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them requested further clearance.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on inspection findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations regarding VAT management.</seg>
<seg id="29">The subsequent inspection action performed was used to evaluate measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The inspection further focused e.g. on selected cases of high-risk intracommunitary transactions, mutual assistance in recovery of claims and VAT checks on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the inspection of VAT management in selected areas in both countries, inspectors have reached the following inspection findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions for registration of payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel checks, comparing VAT registration systems in both countries identified differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">Since various forms of registration cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonizing conditions for registration of payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation was presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">Proposal for amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 1798/2003 218/92 (hereinafter referred to as ′′ Council Regulation (EC) No 218/92 1798/2003 ′′) requested the extension of existing databases within the EU, including VAT tax identification numbers database.</seg>
<seg id="38">He also adjusted common standards for registration and deregistration of tax payers.</seg>
<seg id="39">SAI expected EU Member States to agree on adequate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of the document agreed by EU Member States within ECOFIN does not contain the issue anymore.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret to say that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to consider this project a relevant tool for prevention in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports</seg>
<seg id="44">In the context of international cooperation, it was recommended in the previous control action that all EU countries should introduce a monthly deadline for submitting summary reports and thus allow for more timely examination of the values of intracommunitary transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive Article 2008/117 (2008/117) EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion related to intra-Community transactions reduces the period for summary reports of intra-EU transactions to one a month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1. January 2010, implemented in Germany since July 1., 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to report summary reports monthly was not introduced within the specified deadline in accordance with the applicable EU regulations, while in the Czech Republic did.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and summary reports in Germany in order to achieve greater reliability of VIES data and consideration of interconnection of both VAT returns systems and summary reports</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted BRH recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is ongoing and BRH will monitor further developments in detail.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing successful criteria, components and approaches of the EU risk management system Based on the results of previous inspection action, both SAI agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system must be exchanged and introduced in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the offenders of fraudulent activity will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The inspection found that our two Member States use different risk management systems that have their advantages and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the NKA checked the EUROCANET system, which allows information exchange within the EU, while BRH focused on German participation in the so-called. risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Subsequent inspection of selected cases of intracommunitary transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous inspection action, commercial transactions were jointly examined, where there were doubts about their implementation or irregularity in the reporting of commercial transactions in tax returns or summary reports to the tax payer from both countries.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAIs selected nine cases for subsequent inspection, which included intracommunitary movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">Checks carried out by the tax authorities of the countries concerned were not closed on the date of completion of our previous joint control action.</seg>
<seg id="60">The subsequent inspection action verified that most tax proceedings in connection with the selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany were closed and that adequate measures were taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional VAT measurements or avoidance of tax refund at the entrance).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Checking selected cases of risk intracommunitary transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intracommunitary transactions performed by EU payers, which were included in the EUROCANET system were selected for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="63">The EUROCANET system is a tool for detecting risk tax payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States participation in this system is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in the EUROCANET system, while Germany has passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant of the system if some Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">Given the fact that the German tax administration did not participate in the exchange of data in the EUROCANET system, it was not possible to obtain any information about which suppliers with German VAT ID were evaluated as hazardous.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKÚ identified both cases of normal commercial transactions and cases with suspicion of carousel shops or VAT fraudulent conduct.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax administrators have limited options for controlling risk transactions, especially when it comes to so-called. missing traders, with mere physical vetting of documents can hardly prove any fraudulent behavior to the tax body.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation for tax administrators occurs when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intracommunitary carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases it would be appropriate to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities to identify goods and irregularities in transport documentation and also monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the end consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, hesitates to actively engage in the EUROCANET system because of the absence of sufficient legal base.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are being used to detect risk tax payers, which have been proven to the German tax administration until now.</seg>
<seg id="74">In this field it is necessary to communicate and exchange experience among EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council has reached political agreement on the proposal for a regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">Experience gained so far using the EUROCANET system should be the basis for creating this new VAT fraud network.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance in recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the field of international aid in the recovery of claims, all EU Member States are governed by the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the method of handling applications for international aid in the Czech Republic and Germany is the same.</seg>
<seg id="81">NKÚ and BRH compared the statistics submitted by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs find it useful to renegotiate at EU level to find a way to avoid persistent inconsistencies.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, SAI agrees that reliable statistics should include more information about VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be helpful if the Commission, based on more detailed statistics, was to process analysis to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">According to both SAIs, this means assistance for Member States with low enforcement success rate to increase the level of recovery to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should actively participate in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">SAI analysed the legal situation regarding VAT control for large tax entities (hereinafter also ′′ VDS ′′) in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from tax administrators on areas that SAI consider essential to the management of the issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">The answers received clearly indicate that the situation in both countries develops differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system based on a large volume of relevant data to direct the selection of cases with a tendency to risk (e.g. information from tax checks carried out, balance sheet data and profit and loss statements etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures effective management and analysis of VAT checks in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">The establishment of a specialised VDS finance office is planned in 2012</seg>
<seg id="96">There is no similar system in Germany yet, which makes it difficult to manage and analyse VAT checks in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">Germany has so far more focused on the selection of individual cases in question, especially based on VAT tax return data and summary report.</seg>
<seg id="98">Analysis of this data relies on various components of risk management that will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. The course of the inspection action</seg>
