<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">Differences in the replies of both Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects a lot of data from tax checks carried out and data from accounts - balance sheet and profit and loss accounts.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to direct the selection of cases with risk inclined.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to VAT analysis and management in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the Czech Republic is planned to set up a specialised VDS management financial authority.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">This shows that it is more difficult to perform these tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places greater emphasis on choosing individual cases based on data from submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">Risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">Based on adequate reference comments, expert auditors must be able to calculate the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that Member States should be able to provide adequate financial management and adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help reduce VAT income outages.</seg>
<seg id="616">The result will increase VAT revenue and the risk detection rate for unreliable entrepreneurs will improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of both SAIs on parallel VAT management checks met the goals set by NKÚ and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">Both SAIs have better recognized each other's valid systems in the following areas: • intracommunitary transactions, • VAT risk management, especially regarding the selection of risk-inclined transactions, • VAT recovery assistance and a VAT control for large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud cases and differences in the above mentioned VAT management areas in the Czech Republic and Germany were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">Check findings were compared and best practices were identified based on them.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will become an impetus for stakeholders to start discussions on approaches and strategies within Member States, among them and at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">Extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of both SAIs can serve as an encouragement to carry out future VAT control actions.</seg>
